This is PD-D-1 of the Epic close cycle. Your job: read everything under this Epic and leave behind an **Exit Criteria verification table** in `current-note.md` so a human can decide whether the Epic is done.

## What to read

- The Epic file (under `epics/` — the one matching this run's epic slug, passed to the engine as `--epic <slug>`). Read its **Outcome** and **Exit Criteria**.
- Every ticket under this Epic: `tickets/done/*.md` whose frontmatter `epic_id` matches the slug. Note what each delivered and any deferrals recorded in their `# Out of scope` sections.
- The git log on this Epic's branch (everything since it diverged from `main`) to see the actually-implemented scope.
- `product-brief.md` if present, to ground the Outcome in the product intent.

## What to produce

Append a `## {{ nodeId }} (round {{ round }})` section to `current-note.md` containing an Exit Criteria table — one row per Exit Criterion, no blank cells:

| Exit Criterion | class | status | evidence |
|---|---|---|---|
| <criterion text> | unit-test / integration / real-env | verified / unverified / user_accepted | <ticket slug + AC, test path, log path, screenshot, command output — or, if unverified, why> |

Rules:
  - `class` uses the same scheme as ticket AC: `unit-test-sufficient`, `integration-required`, `real-env-required`. A `real-env-required` criterion needs evidence from the real provider / real environment — a passing mock does NOT verify it.
  - `verified` — concrete evidence exists; cite it. For criteria covered by a closed ticket, point at that ticket's verification (its AC table / `verification.md` / screenshots).
  - `unverified` — no such evidence yet. Say why, and whether the gap needs a new ticket, belongs in another Epic, or is a real-env check that was never run.
  - `user_accepted` — only if the note / ticket history shows the human explicitly accepted the gap. Do not invent acceptance and do not self-defer; deferral is the human's call at the close gate.
  - If any criterion is `unverified`, add a one-line recommendation: which criteria block the close and what would unblock them.

## Constraints

- Do not edit source code. Use Read tools (and Bash only for `git log` and similar inspection).
- Do not commit — the runtime owns commits; your note edits are folded into one commit by the engine.
